Data Analysis Sorter — Sort Dataset in Non-Decreasing Order

In a data analysis system, you are given an array of integers that represents a dataset. You need to sort the dataset in non-decreasing order to perform further statistical analysis on it. The dataset may contain a large number of integers, and you need to sort the array efficiently.

Your task is to implement an algorithm that sorts the given array of integers.

Input format :
First line contains an integer n — the number of elements in the dataset
Second line contains n space-separated integers representing the array nums[]
Output format :
Print the sorted array as a single line of space-separated integers in non-decreasing order
Code constraints :
The number of integers in the array n will be between 1 and 10^5

The integers in the array can be between −10^5 and 10^5

Sample test cases :
Input 1 :
4
3 1 4 2
Output 1 :
1 2 3 4 
Input 2 :
6
-3 1 -4 1 5 -2
Output 2 :
-4 -3 -2 1 1 5

Solution:


// You are using GCC
// You are using GCC
#include<bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main(){
    
    int n;
    cin>>n;
    
    vector<int> arr(n);
    
    for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
        cin>>arr[i];
    }
    
    sort(arr.begin(),arr.end());
    
    for(int i:arr){
        cout<<i<<" ";
    }
}
